 \"Best Bang for the Buck\" rankings of colleges and universities. After becoming accredited in 2006 Cascadia College was named the second best community college in the nation, behind Atlanta Technical College.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2007/0709.careyessay.html |title=America's Best Community Colleges |author=Kevin Carey |magazine=[[The Washington Monthly]] |date=June 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080212062251/http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2007/0709.careyessay.html |archivedate=February 12, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2007/0709.careycascadia.html |title=Built to Teach |author=Kevin Carey |magazine=[[The Washington Monthly]] |date=June 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080119100445/http://www2.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2007/0709.careycascadia.html |archivedate=January 19, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2007/0709.ccrankings.html |title=Community College Rankings |magazine=[[The Washington Monthly]] |date=June 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080212061537/http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2007/0709.ccrankings.html |archivedate=February 12, 2008 }}</ref> UW Bothell has an enrollment of over 6,000 students, of which 13 percent are from Snohomish County.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=December 3, 2017 |title=What draws so many Snohomish County students to UW Bothell? |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/county-leaving-an-imprint-on-uw-bothell/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSchools for Bothell students in grades kindergarten through 12th grade are part of the [[Northshore School District]] while private schools include Cedar Park Christian Schools serving preschool through 12th grade. Heritage Christian Academy serving kindergarten through 9th grades.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hcabothell.org |title=Heritage Christian Academy |author=Dustin Secrest |publisher=}}</ref> Schools in Northshore School district include Fernwood Elementary, Crystal Springs Elementary, Canyon Creek Elementary, Shelton View Elementary, Westhill Elementary, Lockwood Elementary, Frank Love Elementary, Maywood Hills Elementary, Woodmoor Elementary, Woodin Elementary, Northshore Junior High School, Canyon Park Junior High School, Skyview Junior High School, [[Bothell High School]], [[Inglemoor High School]], and Secondary Academy for Success. [[North Creek High School]] opened in the [[North Creek, Washington|North Creek]] area of the city in 2017.\n\n==Government and politics==\n\nBothell has a [[council\u2013manager government]] governed by a [[city council]] consisting of seven council members, each of whom is elected to a four-year term. Council elections are held every two years, with either three or four positions standing, depending upon the class. All positions are nonpartisan and at-large. The Council passes ordinances and resolutions, approves the budget, sets policies and adjudicates issues, and elects from its own membership a mayor and deputy mayor for two-year terms.<ref>{{cite web |title=City Leadership |url=http://www.ci.bothell.wa.us/618/City-Leadership |publisher=City of Bothell |accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDay-to-day affairs in the city are administered by a [[City Manager]] hired by the council. The current city manager is Jennifer Phillips and the mayor is Liam Olsen.<ref>{{Cite web |title=City Leadership Team |url=http://www.bothellwa.gov/247/City-Leadership-Team |publisher=Bothell WA |accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Civic events===\n[[Image:BothellConcordReenact05.jpg|thumb|right|Freedom Festival 2005]]\nMajor annual events throughout the year in Bothell include:\n* The City of Bothell Freedom Festival, a two-day festival celebrating American Independence, including an annual Fourth of July parade and a reenactment of the Battle of Concord on the Bothell Landing Bridge.\n* The Music in the Park concert series, every Friday in July and August at Bothell Landing Amphitheater.\n* Greater Bothell Arts & Crafts Fair\n* City of Bothell Riverfest\n* The Summits of Bothell bike ride<ref>[http://www.summits-of-bothell.org/ Summits of Bothell] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514064200/http://www.summits-of-bothell.org/ |date=May 14, 2008 }}, Bothell Arts Council</ref>\n* La Fiesta Viva!, a celebration of Latino cultural heritage, at Country Village.\n* Harvest Festival and Pumpkin Carving, at Country Village.\n* Tree Lighting and Santa Arrival, at Bothell Landing.\n* The Bothell Farmer's Market at Country Village.\n\nThe Cup of Kindness day, held on May 10, was cited by ''[[Reader's Digest]]'' in its awarding of \"Nicest Places in America\" honors to Bothell and nine other cities in 2018.<ref>{{cite press release |date=June 20, 2018 |title=Reader's Digest Reveals the 2018 Top Ten \"Nicest Places In America\" |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/readers-digest-reveals-the-2018-top-ten-nicest-places-in-america-300669477.html |publisher=[[Reader's Digest]] |accessdate=October 26, 2018}}; {{cite magazine |title=FINALIST: Bothell, WA \u2014 'FOR A DAY OR A LIFETIME' and 'PEOPLE ARE JUST PLAIN NICE' |url=https://www.rd.com/nicestplaces/bothell-wa/ |magazine=[[Reader's Digest]] |accessdate=October 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\n{{Refimprove section|date=December 2018}}\n\nBothell's [[Pop Keeney Stadium]] hosts games for several local high schools, including Inglemoor, Woodinville, and Bothell High Schools, even though the stadium was originally Bothell High School's and serves as its most important tenant. Football games at Pop Keeney have become major cultural and, to an extent, spiritual, gatherings for the community.\n\n===Popular culture===\nIn December 1962, [[Life (magazine)|LIFE Magazine]] recognized Bothell's {{convert|112|ft|m|adj=on}} [[Christmas tree]] as the largest living Christmas tree in the world. However, in the late 1970s, disease attacked the tree, and the top had to be removed.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Local News {{!}} The Birth Of Bothell {{!}} Seattle Times Newspaper|url = http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19981015&slug=2777725|website = community.seattletimes.nwsource.com|access-date = January 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, about 5,000 to 7,000 people gathered for a parade and outdoor concert at the Veterans Memorial Amphitheater at Bothell Landing in honor of local [[American Idol]] contestant [[Blake Lewis]].<ref>[http://www.seattlepi.com/tv/315355_blake12.html 'Idol' mania hits home as Blake Lewis returns], [[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]], May 11, 2007</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1910= 599\n|1920= 613\n|1930= 818\n|1940= 794\n|1950= 1019\n|1960= 2237\n|1970= 5420\n|1980= 7943\n|1990= 12345\n|2000= 30150\n|2010= 33505\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=46657\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\">{{cite web |date= |title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates |url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref><br>2018 Estimate<ref name=\"2018 Pop Estimate\">{{cite web|title=Population Estimates|url=https://census.gov/data/tables/2018/demo/popest/total-cities-and-towns.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"wwwcensusgov\">{{cite web |title=U.S. Census website |url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> of 2010, there were 33,505 people, 13,497 households, and 8,779 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|2764.4|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 14,255 housing units at an average density of {{convert|1176.2|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|racial makeup]] of the city was 79.7% White, 1.6% African American, 0.6% Native American, 10.2% Asian, 0.2% Pacific Islander, 3.4% from other races, and 4.5% from two or more races. Hispanic or Latino of any race were 8.7% of the population.\n\nThere were 13,497 households of which 32.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 51.9% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 9.1% had a female householder with no husband present, 4.1% had a male householder with no wife present, and 35.0% were non-families. 27.2% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.46 and the average family size was 3.00.\n\nThe median age in the city was 38.3 years. 22.4% of residents were under the age of 18; 8.1% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 29.3% were from 25 to 44; 28.1% were from 45 to 64; and 12.1% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 48.8% male and 51.2% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]] of 2000, there were 30,150 people, 11,923 households, and 7,928 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 2,501.5 people per square mile (966.1/km<sup>2</sup>). There were 12,303 housing units at an average density of 1,020.8 per square mile (394.2/km<sup>2</sup>).\n\nAs of the [[2000 United States Census|2000 census]], there are 11,923 households, out of which 33.9% have children under the age of 18 living with them, 53.9% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 8.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 33.5% were non-families. 25.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 7.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.51 and the average family size was 3.05.\n\nIn the city the population was spread out with 25.2% under the age of 18, 8.1% from 18 to 24, 33.2% from 25 to 44, 24.0% from 45 to 64, and 9.5% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 36 years. For every 100 females, there were 96.1 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 93.2 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $59,264, and the median income for a family was $68,580. Males had a median income of $48,476 versus $34,385 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $26,483. About 3.6% of families and 5.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 5.0% of those under age 18 and 5.0% of those age 65 or over.\n\n===Politics===\nIn the [[2004 United States presidential election|2004 U.S. presidential election]], Bothell cast 56.29% of its vote for [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[John Kerry]].<ref>[http://www.uselectionatlas.org/ Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections], uselectionatlas.org</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nBothell was until recently predominantly a [[bedroom community]] with most of its residents working outside of the city. Starting in the 1990s, several businesses opened offices in Bothell, creating a regional employment center providing about 20,000 jobs. Many of these businesses are located in the Canyon Park and North Creek business districts.{{Citation needed|date=September 2008}}\n\n[[Biotechnology]] is a key industry, with OncoGenex Pharmaceuticals,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2008466639_oncogenex04.html |title=Bothell-based OncoGenex says prostate-cancer drug shows promise |newspaper=[[Seattle Times]] |date=December 4, 2008}}</ref> [[Seattle Genetics]],<ref>[http://www.seagen.com/contact_us.shtml Seattle Genetics Contact Page] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716024943/http://www.seagen.com/contact_us.shtml |date=July 16, 2011 }}, September 30, 2009</ref> CMC Icos,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/biotech/2008211947_icos29.html |title=CMC Icos plans $35M expansion of biotech plant in Bothell |newspaper=[[Seattle Times]] |date=September 29, 2008}}</ref> [[Alder Biopharmaceuticals]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.alderbio.com/22/CONTACT/ |title=Alder Pharmaceuticals Contact Page |date=September 30, 2009 |publisher=alderbio.com}}</ref> MDRNA,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mdrnainc.com/mdrna/corp_facts |title=MDRNA Corporate Facts |publisher=mdrna.com |date=September 30, 2009 |access-date=September 30, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090916003236/http://www.mdrnainc.com/mdrna/corp_facts |archive-date=September 16, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Blue Heron Biotechnology,<ref>[http://www.blueheronbio.com/contact Contact Blue Heron Bio] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100526153925/http://www.blueheronbio.com/contact |date=May 26, 2010 }}, September 30, 2009</ref> [[Amgen]],<ref name=\"amgen.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.amgen.com/about/locations.html |title=Amgen - About Amgen - Locations |work=amgen.com |accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref> Iverson Genetic Diagnostics,<ref name=\"futureofbothell.com\">{{cite web |url=http://futureofbothell.com/locating-a-business/area-employers |title=Bothell Landing - Locating a Business in Bothell - Area Employers |publisher=Futureofbothell.com |accessdate=July 12, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140630001252/http://futureofbothell.com/locating-a-business/area-employers |archive-date=June 30, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and Elitech (formerly Epoch Biosciences and Nanogen)<ref name=\"amgen.com\"/> all opening in Bothell. Medical device manufacturers are also located in Bothell, including [[Philips Medical Systems]]<ref name=\"futureofbothell.com\"/> and [[Lockheed Martin]] Aculight.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aculight.com/Downloads/aculight-closing-press-release.pdf |format=PDF |title=Lockheed Martin Completes Acquisition of Aculight Corporation |date=September 2, 2008 |publisher=aculight.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090320015623/http://www.aculight.com/Downloads/aculight-closing-press-release.pdf |archivedate=March 20, 2009 }}</ref> Medical device company [[Ventec Life Systems]] is based in Bothell and manufactures [[ventilator]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Geoff |date=March 27, 2020 |title=Trump orders GM to make ventilators for coronavirus fight after it agreed to produce them with Bothell's Ventec |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/bothells-ventec-and-general-motors-moving-ahead-with-plans-to-build-10000-ventilators-a-month-for-coronavirus-fight/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nComputer technology, data, and [[telecommunication]]s are well represented, and include companies such as [[AT&T Inc.|AT&T]],<ref name=\"futureofbothell.com\"/> AVST,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.avst.com/contact_us/offices.asp |title=AVST Offices |publisher=}}</ref> [[Kinesis (keyboard)|Kinesis]], [[Leviton|Leviton Voice & Data]], Systems Interface, Silicon Mechanics, [[Boeing]], Lockheed Martin, [[Sonosite|SonoSite]] (owned by [[Fujifilm]]), [[T-Mobile]],<ref name=\"futureofbothell.com\"/> [[Panasonic Avionics Corporation]],<ref name=\"futureofbothell.com\"/> Parity Corporation, Vertafore, Allocent, [[Teltone Corporation|Teltone]], and [[Google]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.geekwire.com/2011/war-talent-continues-google-opens-mysterious-bothell-location-expands-fremont/ |title=Google Opens Mysterious Bothell Location |author=John Cook |work=GeekWire}}</ref> [[Microsoft]] had a Canyon Park campus in the early 2000s<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.powerstudies.com/projects/Microsoft-CanyonPark.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 17, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121116101005/http://www.powerstudies.com/projects/Microsoft-CanyonPark.htm |archivedate=November 16, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.com/science/discoveries/news/2001/01/41412 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 17, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111205120943/http://www.wired.com/science/discoveries/news/2001/01/41412 |archivedate=December 5, 2011 }} Why</ref>\n\nEngineering firms, including [[electrical engineering]], [[environmental engineering]], and [[civil engineering]], are well represented. Examples include [[SNC-Lavalin]], [[RH2 Engineering]],<ref>[http://www.rh2.com/content.asp?ContentType=Contacts RH2 Offices] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100906141310/http://www.rh2.com/content.asp?ContentType=Contacts |date=September 6, 2010 }}</ref> Romac Industries, [[North Creek Analytical]], [[ECS Engineering]], [[Emulex]], and [[Path Engineers]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2008}} Bothell also has companies working on new or improved energy technologies, including [[Neah Power Systems]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://selectra.co.uk/energy/guides/market/neah-power |title=Contact Neah Power Systems |author=Thermal Exposure |access-date=August 16, 2010 |archive-url=https://selectra.co.uk/energy/guides/market/neah-power |archive-date=August 4, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[US Army]] has a Reserve facility in the northwest part of the city. ''[[The Seattle Times]]'' moved its main production facility to the North Creek business district in Bothell in 2001, and national magazine publisher [[Scotsman guide]] Media also is headquartered in the city.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsmanguide.com/default.asp?ID=284 |title=Contact Scotsman Guide |publisher=}}</ref> Defunct retailer [[Pacific Linen]] was once based in Bothell until 1996.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://seattle.bizjournals.com/seattle/stories/1996/08/26/story5.html |title=Pacific Linen moves to cheaper headquarters |work=Puget Sound Business Journal}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n<!-- PLEASE RESPECT ALPHABETICAL ORDER -->\n* [[Bryan Alvarez]], professional wrestler and radio host\n* [[Bernadette Bascom]], singer<ref>{{cite news |date=November 7, 2013 |title=Bothell based Northshore Wranglers raise voices in song Dec. 6 |url=https://www.bothell-reporter.com/news/bothell-based-northshore-wranglers-raise-voices-in-song-dec-6/ |work=Bothell Reporter |accessdate=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Ross Bowers (American football)|Ross Bowers]], American football player\n* [[Karan Brar]], actor\n* [[Kyle Cease]], comedian and actor\n* [[Michael Dahlquist]], musician\n* [[Robert DeLong]], electronic musician\n* [[Michael Dong]], skateboarder\n* [[Cori Enghusen]], aka Korel Engin, basketball player\n* [[Brenden Foster]], 11-year-old boy with leukemia who gained national attention for his concern for the homeless\n* [[Phil Harris (fisherman)|Phil Harris]], fisherman and reality TV star\n* [[Johnny Hekker]], American football player\n* [[Zach LaVine]], basketball player\n* [[Blake Lewis]], ''[[American Idol]]'' 2007 runner-up\n* [[Patty Murray]], U.S. Senator since 1993\n* [[Tracie Ruiz|Tracie Ruiz-Conforto]], Olympic medalist in synchronized swimming\n* [[Ernie Steele]], American football player\n* [[Hal Sutherland]], animator and painter\n* [[Rob Thompson (director)|Rob Thompson]], film and television writer/producer/director\n* [[Cody Votolato]], musician ([[The Blood Brothers (band)]])\n* Doug Walker, media personality ([[Nostalgia Critic]])\n* [[Chris Walla]], musician ([[Death Cab for Cutie]])\n* [[Doug Yule]], musician\n\n==See also==\n*[[Flute Quest]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Bothell, Washington}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.ci.bothell.wa.us/ }}\n* {{dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Washington/Localities/B/Bothell/}}\n\n{{King County, Washington}}\n{{Snohomish County, Washington}}\n{{Geographic Location\n|Northwest = [[Brier, Washington|Brier]]\n|North = [[Mill Creek, Washington|Mill Creek]]\n|Northeast = [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]]\n|West = [[Kenmore, Washington|Kenmore]]\n|Center = Bothell\n|East = [[Woodinville, Washington|Woodinville]]\n|Southwest = [[Kirkland, Washington|Kirkland]]\n|South = [[Kirkland, Washington|Kirkland]]\n|Southeast = [[Woodinville, Washington|Woodinville]]\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bothell, Washington]]\n[[Category:Cities in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Cities in King County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1870]]\n[[Category:Cities in Snohomish County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Cities in the Seattle metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:1870 establishments in Washington Territory]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{redirect|Mays Pond|the lake in New York|Mays Pond (New York)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Bothell, Washington\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|motto                    = Welcome to Bothell for a day, or a lifetime\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = Main Street in Bothell, Washington\n|image_seal               = City-of-bothell-new-logo.photograph2.jpg\n|image_skyline            = Bothell-main-street.jpg\n|image_map                = King_County_Washington_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Bothell_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Bothell within [[King County, Washington|King County]]\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             = \n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Washington|Counties]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[King County, Washington|King]], [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish]]\n|government_type          = [[Council\u2013manager government|Council\u2013manager]]\n|leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name              = Liam Olsen\n|leader_title1            = [[City manager]]\n|leader_name1             = Jennifer Phillips\n|established_date         = \n|area_magnitude           = 1 E8\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web |title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files |url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_53.txt |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|area_total_km2           = 35.31\n|area_land_km2            = 35.31\n|area_water_km2           = 0.00\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 46657\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes        = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\"/>\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name=\"wwwcensusgov\"/>\n|population_total         = 33505\n|population_density_km2   = 1321.17\n|population_density_sq_mi = 3421.86\n|timezone                 = [[Pacific Standard Time|PST]]\n|utc_offset               = -8\n|timezone_DST             = [[Pacific Daylight Time|PDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST           = -7\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 13.63\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 13.63\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.00\n|elevation_m              = 23\n|elevation_ft             = 75\n|coordinates              = {{coord|47|46|18|N|122|12|16|W|region:US-WA|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 98011 (King), 98012, 98021 (Snohomish), 98041 (PO boxes)\n|area_code                = [[Area code 425|425]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 53-07380\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1512020<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite gnis |id=1512020 |name=Bothell}}</ref>\n|website                  = {{URL|www.bothellwa.gov}}\n|footnotes                = \n}}\n\n'''Bothell''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u0252|\u03b8|\u0259l}}) is a city in [[King County, Washington|King]] and [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish]] counties in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Washington (state)|Washington]]. It is part of the [[Seattle metropolitan area]].<ref name=\"2010 Census (City)\">{{cite web |title=2010 Census Redistricting Data (Public Law 94-171) Summary File |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_PL_GCTPL2.ST13&prodType=table |work=American FactFinder |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=November 17, 2012 }}{{dead link|bot=medic|date=April 2020}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]] it had a population of 33,505,<ref name=\"wwwcensusgov\"/> and in 2018 the estimated population was 46,657.<ref name=\"USCensusEst2017\">{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2017.html |title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates |accessdate=March 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Bothell Pioneer Cemetery 01.jpg|thumb|left|Historical plaque at [[Bothell Pioneer Cemetery]]. The cemetery founded in 1889, is listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places listings in King County, Washington|National Register of Historic Places]].]]\nPrior to European settlement, the [[Sammamish River]] valley from [[Lake Washington]] to Issaquah Creek south and upstream of Lake Sammamish was inhabited by a population of as many as 200 Native Americans known as the [[Sammamish people]]. The Sammamish were relocated after the [[Puget Sound War]] in 1856 to reservations and non-reservation lands.<ref name=\"Sammamish\">{{cite web |author=Wilma, David |url=http://www.historylink.org/essays/output.cfm?file_id=4190 |title=Bothell -- Thumbnail History |publisher=[[HistoryLink.org]] |work=Essay 4190 |date=June 12, 2003 |accessdate=May 13, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 1870, Columbus S. Greenleaf and George R. Wilson filed land claims in the area formerly inhabited by the Sammamish near present-day Bothell, and built homes. Eight families followed over the next six years. In 1876, Canadian George Brackett bought land and began commercial logging out of a camp located on the north bank of the Sammamish River in what is now the heart of downtown Bothell. A store, school, and sawmill followed over the next several years.\n\nIn 1885, Brackett sold {{convert|80|acre}} to David Bothell, a settler from [[Pennsylvania]]. The town's first postmaster, who bought his property from Bothell, named the town in his honor when it was [[plat]]ted in 1888.<ref>{{cite book |last=Phillips |first=James W. |year=1971 |title=Washington State Place Names |page=[https://archive.org/details/washingtonstatep00phil/page/17 17] |publisher=[[University of Washington Press]] |isbn=0-295-95158-3 |oclc=1052713900 |url=https://archive.org/details/washingtonstatep00phil |url-access=registration |via=[[The Internet Archive]] |accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> Later that same year, a local railroad was built through the town to transport coal from [[Issaquah, Washington|Issaquah]]. Bothell was officially incorporated on April 14, 1909.<ref name=\"Sammamish\"/>\n\nBothell continued to grow as logging expanded and boat traffic brought increasing amounts of goods and passengers up and down the river. As more people moved into the area, the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|Army Corps of Engineers]] decided to dredge and straighten the river in the years shortly after Bothell's incorporation. Most boat traffic came to an abrupt end only a few years later when Lake Washington was lowered in 1917. Water transport also shifted to trucks after a brick road was built from Seattle. The logging economy declined quickly around the same time, and the local economy shifted to farming.<ref name=\"Sammamish\"/>\n\nAfter World War II, better highways and a post-war boom brought [[suburban]] development to Bothell. These new neighborhoods and a series of annexations dramatically expanded Bothell's population from about 1,000 in 1950 to over 45,000 as of 2017.<ref>{{cite news |date=November 28, 1965 |title=Bothell Hopes to Remain Residential Community |page=40 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> In 1992, the city annexed an area in southern Snohomish County, becoming a dual-county city and adding 11,400 people.<ref>{{cite news |last=Carlton Harrell |first=Debera |date=February 15, 1997 |title=A logging and farm town yields to people and high technology |page=D1 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref> Bothell was mostly a [[bedroom community]] for people working in Seattle until the 1990s, when business development brought new jobs to create a regional employment center in Canyon Park with about 20,000 jobs, many in high technology sectors such as [[biotechnology]] and [[software development]]. In 1990, a campus of the [[University of Washington]] opened in Bothell.<ref name=\"Sammamish\"/>\n\nIn 2010, the city of Bothell began a $150 million program to redevelop downtown, including the demolition of 15 buildings, moving [[Washington State Route 522|State Route 522]], expanding the Bothell\u2013Everett Highway, expanding a city park, and expanding the city hall.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tsong |first=Nicole |date=April 6, 2010 |title=Bothell breaks ground on a grand plan to fix its downtown |page=A1 |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/bothell-breaks-ground-on-a-grand-plan-to-fix-its-downtown/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nA major fire in downtown broke out at the Mercantile Building on July 22, 2016, and damaged and closed more than 20 businesses. The fire dealt a blow to the redevelopment program and required state aid for rebuilding.<ref>{{cite news |last=Coleman |first=Vernal |date=July 22, 2016 |title=Downtown Bothell blaze deals blow to redevelopment efforts |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/buildings-ablaze-as-huge-fire-sweeps-through-downtown-bothell/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nBothell is located at {{coord|47.771670|-122.204421|type:city_region:US|format=dms|display=inline}} (47.771670, -122.204421).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=April 23, 2011 |date=February 12, 2011 |title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> The largest river is the Sammamish, which connects Lake Sammamish to Lake Washington.\n\nAccording to the City of Bothell, the city has a total area of {{convert|13.7|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, all of it land.<ref name=\"Bothell annexation\">{{cite web |title=City of Bothell Annexation 2015 |url=http://www.ci.bothell.wa.us/Annexation/WhyisBothell.ashx?p=1562 |publisher=City of Bothell, Washington |accessdate=November 29, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208063933/http://www.ci.bothell.wa.us/Annexation/WhyisBothell.ashx?p=1562 |archivedate=December 8, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nBothell is a geographical oddity in that it straddles two counties ([[King County, Washington|King]] and [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish]]). Because most streets in Bothell are numbered and not named, streets that cross the county line often change numbers. For example, 104th Avenue NE in King County becomes 23rd Avenue SE when it crosses into Snohomish County.\n\nThe area has several wetlands that are home to large groups of [[crow]]s, up to 16,000 at a time, that commute from the Seattle region to roost in Bothell.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nile |first=Amy |date=April 29, 2016 |title=Thousands of crows darken Bothell's sky, attracting scholars |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/thousands-of-crows-darken-bothells-sky-attracting-scholars/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Doughton |first=Sandi |authorlink=Sandi Doughton |date=January 3, 2018 |title=What's with all the cawing? UW team eavesdrops on crows |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/science/whats-with-all-the-cawing-uw-team-eavesdrops-on-crows/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Neighborhoods and districts===\n[[Image:Sammamish River Bothell WA 01.jpg|thumb|The Sammamish River near downtown Bothell]]\n[[Image:BothellCountryVillageChicken.jpg|thumb|Country Village was an arts mall off the beaten track]]\n\nBothell has several communities, districts, and neighborhoods. These include:\n* [[Anderson School (Bothell, Washington)|Anderson School]] is a former junior high school that currently operates as a renovated restaurant, bar, and hotel, operated by the [[McMenamins]] family chain. \n* Canyon Creek is the residential area east of Canyon Park and south of Maltby Road, with two elementary schools Canyon Creek Elementary, and [[Skyview Junior High School]]. The schools are part of the [[Northshore School District]].\n* Canyon Park is a commercial and business district at the junction of Bothell-Everett Highway and Interstate 405, with several restaurants, shops, and grocery stores, along with several major employers.\n* Downtown Bothell, north of Bothell Way on the north side of the [[Sammamish River]], was an area originally settled by pioneers. It contains a business district along Main Street, and several blocks of residences at the foot of Beckstrom Hill. It also contains city hall and the police station, the Bothell Library, and [[Pop Keeney Stadium]].\n* Fitzgerald is a southern extension of Canyon Park containing Canyon Park Junior High.\n* The Highlands is a neighborhood right next to Canyon Park Junior High.\n* Lake Pleasant/Country Village is the area bordering the wooded and winding portion of Bothell-Everett Highway between downtown and Canyon Park. Lake Pleasant hosts an RV park, and Country Village was an outdoor shopping center that opened in 1981 and closed in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Notice {{!}} Country Village Shops Bothell |url=https://www.countryvillagebothell.com/notice |website=www.countryvillagebothell.com |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>\n* Maywood/Beckstrom Hill is a residential neighborhood on the hill north of downtown, and is the location of Maywood Hills Elementary School, Heritage Christian Academy and St. Brendan's Parish School.\n* [[North Creek, Washington|North Creek]], named for Bothell's second-largest waterway, is a business and light industrial district and community with several large big box retail stores, and the production facility for the ''Seattle Times''. The [[North Creek Forest]] is recently established protected area in this neighborhood. The residential part of North Creek extends to the beginning of the Everett School District and includes Fernwood Elementary and North Creek High School. Much of it is outside of Bothell city limits.\n* Norway Hill is a residential neighborhood overlooking downtown from the south. Since 2014 all of Norway hill is within the Bothell city limits.\n* Pioneer Hills is a residential community on the hills east of North Creek that borders Woodinville, and contains Woodin Elementary School.\n* Queensgate is a residential neighborhood along Brickyard Road, south of the Sammamish River and adjacent to nearby Woodinville.\n* Mays Pond is a residential neighborhood just north of the Bothell's city limits containing Woodside and Cedar Wood Elementary Schools.\n* Queensborough/Brentwood is a residential neighborhood west and north of Canyon Park, containing Frank Love Elementary School and Wallace Swamp Creek Park.\n* Riverfront, south of Bothell Way and mostly along the south side of the river near Riverside Drive, contains Sammamish River Park, Blyth Park, several residences, and the Northshore Senior Center.\n* Waynita is a residential neighborhood along Waynita Way between Wayne Curve and nearby Juanita. The former Wayne Golf Course, now a city-owned parkland, is in Waynita.<ref>{{cite news |last=Watanabe |first=Ben |date=April 2, 2018 |title=Bothell's largest park is open to visitors and name ideas |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/bothells-largest-park-is-open-to-visitors-and-name-ideas/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n* Westhill is a mid-20th century residential expansion on the hill to the west of downtown, and includes [[Bothell High School]] and Westhill Elementary School.\n* Shelton View is a residential neighborhood north of Westhill in Snohomish County containing Shelton View Elementary.\n* Thrasher's Corner is a retail district mostly outside the city limits of Bothell, that along with the residential Red Hawk neighborhood to the east is part of the city's official planning area.\nPrior to 1993, the nearby city of Woodinville was unincorporated, and some of its neighborhoods were considered part of Bothell and were being considered for annexation. The people of Woodinville voted in 1992 to incorporate, and incorporation was official early the next year.\n\n===Climate===\nBothell has a temperate oceanic climate, with cool summers and cool (but not cold) winters. Winter sees much more rainfall than summer and winters in Bothell (much like the rest of the [[Pacific Northwest|PNW]]) are very cloudy and overcast. Summers are drier and cool to warm.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=628054&cityname=Bothell%2C+Washington%2C+United+States+of+America&units= |title=Climate Summary for Bothell, Washington |work=Weatherbase}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Bothell 1981\u20132013 Normals\n|single line = Y\n\n|collapse =\n|Jan high F = 44.1\n|Feb high F = 48.3\n|Mar high F = 52.8\n|Apr high F = 59.9\n|May high F = 66.3\n|Jun high F = 69.6\n|Jul high F = 75.6\n|Aug high F = 74.8\n|Sep high F = 70.7\n|Oct high F = 61.0\n|Nov high F = 51.1\n|Dec high F = 46.6\n|year high F= 60.1\n|Jan low F = 30.6\n|Feb low 