n|source 1 = Weatherbase.com <ref name = WB >\n{{cite web |url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weatherall.php3?s=628054&units= |title=Bothell, Washington Travel Weather Averages (Weatherbase) |publisher=Weatherbase |accessdate=November 23, 2014}}</ref>\n|date=November 2014\n}}\n\n==Education==\nBothell is home to [[Cascadia College]] and the [[University of Washington, Bothell]]. The two institutions share the same campus, which opened in the year 2000. In 2014 the University of Washington Bothell was ranked #37 in the nation among all colleges and universities by Money Magazine and was ranked 6th in the Nation by Washington Monthly in their \"Best Bang for the Buck\" rankings of colleges and universities. After becoming accredited in 2006 Cascadia College was named the second best community college in the nation, behind Atlanta Technical College.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2007/0709.careyessay.html |title=America's Best Community Colleges |author=Kevin Carey |magazine=[[The Washington Monthly]] |date=June 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080212062251/http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2007/0709.careyessay.html |archivedate=February 12, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2007/0709.careycascadia.html |title=Built to Teach |author=Kevin Carey |magazine=[[The Washington Monthly]] |date=June 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080119100445/http://www2.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2007/0709.careycascadia.html |archivedate=January 19, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2007/0709.ccrankings.html |title=Community College Rankings |magazine=[[The Washington Monthly]] |date=June 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080212061537/http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2007/0709.ccrankings.html |archivedate=February 12, 2008 }}</ref> UW Bothell has an enrollment of over 6,000 students, of which 13 percent are from Snohomish County.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=December 3, 2017 |title=What draws so many Snohomish County students to UW Bothell? |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/county-leaving-an-imprint-on-uw-bothell/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSchools for Bothell students in grades kindergarten through 12th grade are part of the [[Northshore School District]] while private schools include Cedar Park Christian Schools serving preschool through 12th grade. Heritage Christian Academy serving kindergarten through 9th grades.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hcabothell.org |title=Heritage Christian Academy |author=Dustin Secrest |publisher=}}</ref> Schools in Northshore School district include Fernwood Elementary, Crystal Springs Elementary, Canyon Creek Elementary, Shelton View Elementary, Westhill Elementary, Lockwood Elementary, Frank Love Elementary, Maywood Hills Elementary, Woodmoor Elementary, Woodin Elementary, Northshore Junior High School, Canyon Park Junior High School, Skyview Junior High School, [[Bothell High School]], [[Inglemoor High School]], and Secondary Academy for Success. [[North Creek High School]] opened in the [[North Creek, Washington|North Creek]] area of the city in 2017.\n\n==Government and politics==\n\nBothell has a [[council\u2013manager government]] governed by a [[city council]] consisting of seven council members, each of whom is elected to a four-year term. Council elections are held every two years, with either three or four positions standing, depending upon the class. All positions are nonpartisan and at-large. The Council passes ordinances and resolutions, approves the budget, sets policies and adjudicates issues, and elects from its own membership a mayor and deputy mayor for two-year terms.<ref>{{cite web |title=City Leadership |url=http://www.ci.bothell.wa.us/618/City-Leadership |publisher=City of Bothell |accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDay-to-day affairs in the city are administered by a [[City Manager]] hired by the council. The current city manager is Jennifer Phillips and the mayor is Liam Olsen.<ref>{{Cite web |title=City Leadership Team |url=http://www.bothellwa.gov/247/City-Leadership-Team |publisher=Bothell WA |accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Civic events===\n[[Image:BothellConcordReenact05.jpg|thumb|right|Freedom Festival 2005]]\nMajor annual events throughout the year in Bothell include:\n* The City of Bothell Freedom Festival, a two-day festival celebrating American Independence, including an annual Fourth of July parade and a reenactment of the Battle of Concord on the Bothell Landing Bridge.\n* The Music in the Park concert series, every Friday in July and August at Bothell Landing Amphitheater.\n* Greater Bothell Arts & Crafts Fair\n* City of Bothell Riverfest\n* The Summits of Bothell bike ride<ref>[http://www.summits-of-bothell.org/ Summits of Bothell] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514064200/http://www.summits-of-bothell.org/ |date=May 14, 2008 }}, Bothell Arts Council</ref>\n* La Fiesta Viva!, a celebration of Latino cultural heritage, at Country Village.\n* Harvest Festival and Pumpkin Carving, at Country Village.\n* Tree Lighting and Santa Arrival, at Bothell Landing.\n* The Bothell Farmer's Market at Country Village.\n\nThe Cup of Kindness day, held on May 10, was cited by ''[[Reader's Digest]]'' in its awarding of \"Nicest Places in America\" honors to Bothell and nine other cities in 2018.<ref>{{cite press release |date=June 20, 2018 |title=Reader's Digest Reveals the 2018 Top Ten \"Nicest Places In America\" |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/readers-digest-reveals-the-2018-top-ten-nicest-places-in-america-300669477.html |publisher=[[Reader's Digest]] |accessdate=October 26, 2018}}; {{cite magazine |title=FINALIST: Bothell, WA \u2014 'FOR A DAY OR A LIFETIME' and 'PEOPLE ARE JUST PLAIN NICE' |url=https://www.rd.com/nicestplaces/bothell-wa/ |magazine=[[Reader's Digest]] |accessdate=October 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\n{{Refimprove section|date=December 2018}}\n\nBothell's [[Pop Keeney Stadium]] hosts games for several local high schools, including Inglemoor, Woodinville, and Bothell High Schools, even though the stadium was originally Bothell High School's and serves as its most important tenant. Football games at Pop Keeney have become major cultural and, to an extent, spiritual, gatherings for the community.\n\n===Popular culture===\nIn December 1962, [[Life (magazine)|LIFE Magazine]] recognized Bothell's {{convert|112|ft|m|adj=on}} [[Christmas tree]] as the largest living Christmas tree in the world. However, in the late 1970s, disease attacked the tree, and the top had to be removed.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Local News {{!}} The Birth Of Bothell {{!}} Seattle Times Newspaper|url = http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19981015&slug=2777725|website = community.seattletimes.nwsource.com|access-date = January 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, about 5,000 to 7,000 people gathered for a parade and outdoor concert at the Veterans Memorial Amphitheater at Bothell Landing in honor of local [[American Idol]] contestant [[Blake Lewis]].<ref>[http://www.seattlepi.com/tv/315355_blake12.html 'Idol' mania hits home as Blake Lewis returns], [[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]], May 11, 2007</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1910= 599\n|1920= 613\n|1930= 818\n|1940= 794\n|1950= 1019\n|1960= 2237\n|1970= 5420\n|1980= 7943\n|1990= 12345\n|2000= 30150\n|2010= 33505\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=46657\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\">{{cite web |date= |title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates |url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref><br>2018 Estimate<ref name=\"2018 Pop Estimate\">{{cite web|title=Population Estimates|url=https://census.gov/data/tables/2018/demo/popest/total-cities-and-towns.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"wwwcensusgov\">{{cite web |title=U.S. Census website |url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> of 2010, there were 33,505 people, 13,497 households, and 8,779 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|2764.4|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 14,255 housing units at an average density of {{convert|1176.2|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|racial makeup]] of the city was 79.7% White, 1.6% African American, 0.6% Native American, 10.2% Asian, 0.2% Pacific Islander, 3.4% from other races, and 4.5% from two or more races. Hispanic or Latino of any race were 8.7% of the population.\n\nThere were 13,497 households of which 32.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 51.9% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 9.1% had a female householder with no husband present, 4.1% had a male householder with no wife present, and 35.0% were non-families. 27.2% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.46 and the average family size was 3.00.\n\nThe median age in the city was 38.3 years. 22.4% of residents were under the age of 18; 8.1% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 29.3% were from 25 to 44; 28.1% were from 45 to 64; and 12.1% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 48.8% male and 51.2% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]] of 2000, there were 30,150 people, 11,923 households, and 7,928 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 2,501.5 people per square mile (966.1/km<sup>2</sup>). There were 12,303 housing units at an average density of 1,020.8 per square mile (394.2/km<sup>2</sup>).\n\nAs of the [[2000 United States Census|2000 census]], there are 11,923 households, out of which 33.9% have children under the age of 18 living with them, 53.9% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 8.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 33.5% were non-families. 25.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 7.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.51 and the average family size was 3.05.\n\nIn the city the population was spread out with 25.2% under the age of 18, 8.1% from 18 to 24, 33.2% from 25 to 44, 24.0% from 45 to 64, and 9.5% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 36 years. For every 100 females, there were 96.1 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 93.2 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $59,264, and the median income for a family was $68,580. Males had a median income of $48,476 versus $34,385 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $26,483. About 3.6% of families and 5.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 5.0% of those under age 18 and 5.0% of those age 65 or over.\n\n===Politics===\nIn the [[2004 United States presidential election|2004 U.S. presidential election]], Bothell cast 56.29% of its vote for [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[John Kerry]].<ref>[http://www.uselectionatlas.org/ Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections], uselectionatlas.org</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nBothell was until recently predominantly a [[bedroom community]] with most of its residents working outside of the city. Starting in the 1990s, several businesses opened offices in Bothell, creating a regional employment center providing about 20,000 jobs. Many of these businesses are located in the Canyon Park and North Creek business districts.{{Citation needed|date=September 2008}}\n\n[[Biotechnology]] is a key industry, with OncoGenex Pharmaceuticals,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2008466639_oncogenex04.html |title=Bothell-based OncoGenex says prostate-cancer drug shows promise |newspaper=[[Seattle Times]] |date=December 4, 2008}}</ref> [[Seattle Genetics]],<ref>[http://www.seagen.com/contact_us.shtml Seattle Genetics Contact Page] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716024943/http://www.seagen.com/contact_us.shtml |date=July 16, 2011 }}, September 30, 2009</ref> CMC Icos,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/biotech/2008211947_icos29.html |title=CMC Icos plans $35M expansion of biotech plant in Bothell |newspaper=[[Seattle Times]] |date=September 29, 2008}}</ref> [[Alder Biopharmaceuticals]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.alderbio.com/22/CONTACT/ |title=Alder Pharmaceuticals Contact Page |date=September 30, 2009 |publisher=alderbio.com}}</ref> MDRNA,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mdrnainc.com/mdrna/corp_facts |title=MDRNA Corporate Facts |publisher=mdrna.com |date=September 30, 2009 |access-date=September 30, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090916003236/http://www.mdrnainc.com/mdrna/corp_facts |archive-date=September 16, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Blue Heron Biotechnology,<ref>[http://www.blueheronbio.com/contact Contact Blue Heron Bio] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100526153925/http://www.blueheronbio.com/contact |date=May 26, 2010 }}, September 30, 2009</ref> [[Amgen]],<ref name=\"amgen.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.amgen.com/about/locations.html |title=Amgen - About Amgen - Locations |work=amgen.com |accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref> Iverson Genetic Diagnostics,<ref name=\"futureofbothell.com\">{{cite web |url=http://futureofbothell.com/locating-a-business/area-employers |title=Bothell Landing - Locating a Business in Bothell - Area Employers |publisher=Futureofbothell.com |accessdate=July 12, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140630001252/http://futureofbothell.com/locating-a-business/area-employers |archive-date=June 30, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and Elitech (formerly Epoch Biosciences and Nanogen)<ref name=\"amgen.com\"/> all opening in Bothell. Medical device manufacturers are also located in Bothell, including [[Philips Medical Systems]]<ref name=\"futureofbothell.com\"/> and [[Lockheed Martin]] Aculight.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aculight.com/Downloads/aculight-closing-press-release.pdf |format=PDF |title=Lockheed Martin Completes Acquisition of Aculight Corporation |date=September 2, 2008 |publisher=aculight.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090320015623/http://www.aculight.com/Downloads/aculight-closing-press-release.pdf |archivedate=March 20, 2009 }}</ref> Medical device company [[Ventec Life Systems]] is based in Bothell and manufactures [[ventilator]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Geoff |date=March 27, 2020 |title=Trump orders GM to make ventilators for coronavirus fight after it agreed to produce them with Bothell's Ventec |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/bothells-ventec-and-general-motors-moving-ahead-with-plans-to-build-10000-ventilators-a-month-for-coronavirus-fight/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nComputer technology, data, and [[telecommunication]]s are well represented, and include companies such as [[AT&T Inc.|AT&T]],<ref name=\"futureofbothell.com\"/> AVST,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.avst.com/contact_us/offices.asp |title=AVST Offices |publisher=}}</ref> [[Kinesis (keyboard)|Kinesis]], [[Leviton|Leviton Voice & Data]], Systems Interface, Silicon Mechanics, [[Boeing]], Lockheed Martin, [[Sonosite|SonoSite]] (owned by [[Fujifilm]]), [[T-Mobile]],<ref name=\"futureofbothell.com\"/> [[Panasonic Avionics Corporation]],<ref name=\"futureofbothell.com\"/> Parity Corporation, Vertafore, Allocent, [[Teltone Corporation|Teltone]], and [[Google]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.geekwire.com/2011/war-talent-continues-google-opens-mysterious-bothell-location-expands-fremont/ |title=Google Opens Mysterious Bothell Location |author=John Cook |work=GeekWire}}</ref> [[Microsoft]] had a Canyon Park campus in the early 2000s<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.powerstudies.com/projects/Microsoft-CanyonPark.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 17, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121116101005/http://www.powerstudies.com/projects/Microsoft-CanyonPark.htm |archivedate=November 16, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.com/science/discoveries/news/2001/01/41412 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 17, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111205120943/http://www.wired.com/science/discoveries/news/2001/01/41412 |archivedate=December 5, 2011 }} Why</ref>\n\nEngineering firms, including [[electrical engineering]], [[environmental engineering]], and [[civil engineering]], are well represented. Examples include [[SNC-Lavalin]], [[RH2 Engineering]],<ref>[http://www.rh2.com/content.asp?ContentType=Contacts RH2 Offices] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100906141310/http://www.rh2.com/content.asp?ContentType=Contacts |date=September 6, 2010 }}</ref> Romac Industries, [[North Creek Analytical]], [[ECS Engineering]], [[Emulex]], and [[Path Engineers]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2008}} Bothell also has companies working on new or improved energy technologies, including [[Neah Power Systems]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neahpower.com/contact |title=Contact Neah Power Systems |author=Thermal Exposure |access-date=August 16, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100804054611/http://neahpower.com/contact |archive-date=August 4, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[US Army]] has a Reserve facility in the northwest part of the city. ''[[The Seattle Times]]'' moved its main production facility to the North Creek business district in Bothell in 2001, and national magazine publisher [[Scotsman guide]] Media also is headquartered in the city.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsmanguide.com/default.asp?ID=284 |title=Contact Scotsman Guide |publisher=}}</ref> Defunct retailer [[Pacific Linen]] was once based in Bothell until 1996.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://seattle.bizjournals.com/seattle/stories/1996/08/26/story5.html |title=Pacific Linen moves to cheaper headquarters |work=Puget Sound Business Journal}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n<!-- PLEASE RESPECT ALPHABETICAL ORDER -->\n* [[Bryan Alvarez]], professional wrestler and radio host\n* [[Bernadette Bascom]], singer<ref>{{cite news |date=November 7, 2013 |title=Bothell based Northshore Wranglers raise voices in song Dec. 6 |url=https://www.bothell-reporter.com/news/bothell-based-northshore-wranglers-raise-voices-in-song-dec-6/ |work=Bothell Reporter |accessdate=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Ross Bowers (American football)|Ross Bowers]], American football player\n* [[Karan Brar]], actor\n* [[Kyle Cease]], comedian and actor\n* [[Michael Dahlquist]], musician\n* [[Robert DeLong]], electronic musician\n* [[Michael Dong]], skateboarder\n* [[Cori Enghusen]], aka Korel Engin, basketball player\n* [[Brenden Foster]], 11-year-old boy with leukemia who gained national attention for his concern for the homeless\n* [[Phil Harris (fisherman)|Phil Harris]], fisherman and reality TV star\n* [[Johnny Hekker]], American football player\n* [[Zach LaVine]], basketball player\n* [[Blake Lewis]], ''[[American Idol]]'' 2007 runner-up\n* [[Patty Murray]], U.S. Senator since 1993\n* [[Tracie Ruiz|Tracie Ruiz-Conforto]], Olympic medalist in synchronized swimming\n* [[Ernie Steele]], American football player\n* [[Hal Sutherland]], animator and painter\n* [[Rob Thompson (director)|Rob Thompson]], film and television writer/producer/director\n* [[Cody Votolato]], musician ([[The Blood Brothers (band)]])\n* Doug Walker, media personality ([[Nostalgia Critic]])\n* [[Chris Walla]], musician ([[Death Cab for Cutie]])\n* [[Doug Yule]], musician\n\n==See also==\n*[[Flute Quest]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Bothell, Washington}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.ci.bothell.wa.us/ }}\n* {{dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Washington/Localities/B/Bothell/}}\n\n{{King County, Washington}}\n{{Snohomish County, Washington}}\n{{Geographic Location\n|Northwest = [[Brier, Washington|Brier]]\n|North = [[Mill Creek, Washington|Mill Creek]]\n|Northeast = [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]]\n|West = [[Kenmore, Washington|Kenmore]]\n|Center = Bothell\n|East = [[Woodinville, Washington|Woodinville]]\n|Southwest = [[Kirkland, Washington|Kirkland]]\n|South = [[Kirkland, Washington|Kirkland]]\n|Southeast = [[Woodinville, Washington|Woodinville]]\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bothell, Washington]]\n[[Category:Cities in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Cities in King County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1870]]\n[[Category:Cities in Snohomish County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Cities in the Seattle metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:1870 establishments in Washington Territory]]\n", "name_user": "Carly683", "label": "safe", "comment": "broken link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bothell,_Washington"}
{"title_page": "Synonym", "text_new": "{{About|the general meaning of \"synonym\"}}\n{{short description|Words or phrases having the same meaning}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2014}}\n[[File:Library of Ashurbanipal synonym list tablet.jpg|thumb|Synonym list in [[cuneiform]] on a clay tablet, [[Neo-Assyrian]] period<ref>{{British-Museum-db|K.4375|id=308401}}</ref>]]\n\nA '''synonym''' is a word or phrase that means exactly or nearly the same as another word or phrase in the same language. Words that are synonyms are said to be '''synonymous''', and the state of being a synonym is called '''synonymy'''.  For example, the words ''begin'', ''start'', ''commence'', and ''initiate'' are all synonyms of one another. Words are typically synonymous in one particular [[word sense|sense]]: for example, ''long'' and ''extended'' in the [[context (language use)|context]] ''long time'' or ''extended time'' are synonymous, but ''long'' cannot be used in the phrase ''extended family''. Synonyms with exactly the same meaning share a [[seme (semantics)|seme]] or denotational [[sememe]], whereas those with inexactly similar meanings share a broader denotational or [[connotation]]al sememe and thus overlap within a [[semantic field]]. The former are sometimes called [[cognitive synonymy|cognitive synonyms]] and the latter, near-synonyms,<ref name=\"Stanojevi%C4%87_2009\">{{Citation |last=Stanojevi\u0107 |first=Maja |year=2009 |title= Cognitive synonymy: a general overview |journal=Facta Universitatis, Linguistics and Literature series |volume=7 |issue=2 |pages=193\u2013200 | url=/lal/lal200902/lal200902-05.pdf |doi= |postscript=.}}</ref> plesionyms<ref>DiMarco, Chrysanne, and Graeme Hirst. \"Usage notes as the basis for a representation of near-synonymy for lexical choice.\" Proceedings of 9th annual conference of the University of Waterloo Centre for the New Oxford English Dictionary and Text Research. 1993.</ref> or poecilonyms.<ref>Grambs, David. The Endangered English Dictionary: Bodacious Words Your Dictionary Forgot. WW Norton & Company, 1997.</ref>\n\n==Lexicography==\nSome [[lexicographer]]s claim that no synonyms have exactly the same meaning (in all contexts or social levels of language) because [[etymology]], [[orthography]], phonic qualities, [[connotation]]s, ambiguous meanings, [[usage (language)|usage]], and so on make them unique. Different words that are similar in meaning usually differ for a reason: ''feline'' is more formal than ''cat''; ''long'' and ''extended'' are only synonyms in one usage and not in others (for example, a ''long arm'' is not the same as an ''extended arm''). Synonyms are also a source of [[euphemism]]s.\n\n[[Metonymy]] can sometimes be a form of synonymy: ''the [[White House]]'' is used as a synonym of ''the administration'' in referring to the U.S. [[executive (government)|executive branch]] under a specific president.<ref>{{Cite web|url=/A-AMERICA-N/USA/USA-Washington/DC-001.htm|title=World Architecture Images- The White House|website=www.essential-architecture.com|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref> Thus a metonym is a type of synonym, and the word ''metonym'' is a [[hyponymy and hypernymy|hyponym]] of the word ''synonym''.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nThe analysis of synonymy, [[polysemy]], hyponymy, and [[hyponymy and hypernymy|hypernymy]] is inherent to [[taxonomy (general)|taxonomy]] and [[ontology (information science)|ontology]] in the [[information science|information-science]] senses of those terms.<ref>Hirst, Graeme. \"[ftp://ftp.db.toronto.edu/public_html/dist/gh/Hirst-Ontol-2009-as-published.pdf Ontology and the lexicon].\" Handbook on ontologies. Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg, 2009. 269-292.</ref> It has applications in [[pedagogy]] and [[machine learning]], because they rely on [[word-sense disambiguation]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Turney|first=Peter D.|date=2008|title=A Uniform Approach to Analogies, Synonyms, Antonyms, and Associations|url=/citation.cfm?id=1599081.1599195|journal=Proceedings of the 22Nd International Conference on Computational Linguistics - Volume 1|series=COLING '08|location=Stroudsburg, PA, USA|publisher=Association for Computational Linguistics|pages=905\u2013912|isbn=978-1-905593-44-6}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word comes from [[Ancient Greek language|Ancient Greek]] ''s\u00fdn'' ({{lang|grc|[[wikt:\u03c3\u03cd\u03bd|\u03c3\u03cd\u03bd]]}}; \"with\") and ''\u00f3noma'' ({{lang|grc|[[wikt:\u1f44\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03b1|\u1f44\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03b1]]}}; \"name\").\n\n== Examples ==\n[[File:Synonym.png|English language]]\n\nSynonyms can be any [[part of speech]], as long as both words belong to the same part of speech. Examples:\n\n*noun\n**''drink'' and ''beverage''\n*verb\n**''buy'' and ''purchase''\n*adjective\n**''big'' and ''large''\n*adverb\n**''quickly'' and ''speedily''\n*preposition\n** ''on'' and ''upon''\n*noun\n** ''[[Weekly Shonen Sunday]]'' and ''[[Ku Klux Klan]]''\n\nSynonyms are defined with respect to certain senses of words: ''pupil'' as the ''aperture in the iris of the eye'' is not synonymous with ''student''. Such like, ''he expired'' means the same as ''he died'', yet ''my passport has expired'' cannot be replaced by ''my passport has died''.\n\nIn English, many synonyms emerged in the [[Middle Ages]], after the [[Norman conquest of England]]. While England's new ruling class spoke [[Norman French]], the lower classes continued to speak [[Old English]] (Anglo-Saxon). As Old English became more developed, more words would be borrowed from a variety of languages, resulting in more synonyms.<ref>{{Cite book|url=/books?hl=en&lr=&id=3qs0AQAAMAAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PA1&dq=origin+on+english+synonym&ots=dgutkQZOqK&sig=wPqhozO_CsN6CkjZ0eH2lDz51Eo#v=onepage&q=synonym&f=false|title=The Making of English|last=Bradley|first=Henry|date=1922|publisher=Macmillan and Company, Limited|language=en}}</ref> Thus, today we have synonyms like the Norman-derived ''people'', ''liberty'' and ''archer'', and the Saxon-derived ''folk'', ''freedom'' and ''bowman''. For more examples, see the [[list of Germanic and Latinate equivalents in English]].\n\nA [[thesaurus]] lists similar or related words; these are often, but not always, synonyms.\n\n* The word '''''poecilonym''''' is a rare synonym of the word ''synonym''. It is not entered in most major dictionaries and is a curiosity or piece of trivia for being an [[autological word]] because of its [[meta]] quality as a synonym of ''synonym''.\n* '''[[Antonym]]s''' are words with opposite or nearly opposite meanings. For example: ''hot'' \u2194 ''cold'', ''large'' \u2194 ''small'', ''thick'' \u2194 ''thin'', ''synonym'' \u2194 ''antonym'' \n* [[Hyponymy and hypernymy|'''Hypernyms''' and '''hyponyms''']] are words that refer to, respectively, a general category and a specific instance of that category. For example, ''vehicle'' is a hypernym of ''car'', and ''car'' is a hyponym of ''vehicle''.\n* '''[[Homophone]]s''' are words that have the same pronunciation, but different meanings. For example, ''witch'' and ''which'' are homophones in most accents (because they are pronounced the same).\n* '''[[Homograph]]s''' are words that have the same spelling, but have different pronunciations. For example, one can ''record'' a song or keep a ''record'' of documents.\n* '''[[Homonym]]s''' are words that have the same pronunciation and spelling, but have different meanings. For example, ''rose'' (a type of flower) and ''rose'' (past tense of ''rise'') are homonyms.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[-onym]]\n* [[Cognitive synonymy]]\n* [[Elegant variation]], the gratuitous use of a synonym in prose\n* [[Synonym ring]]\n* [[Synonymy in Japanese]]\n* {{Annotated link|Thesaurus|Thesauri and synonym dictionaries}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary}}\nTools which graph words relations:\n* [https://graphwords.com/ GraphWords] \u2013 Online tool for visualization word relations\n* [http://www.synonyms.net/ Synonyms.net] \u2013 Online reference resource that provides instant synonyms and antonyms definitions including visualizations, voice pronunciations and translations\n* [http://www.atlas-semantiques.eu/?l=EN English/French Semantic Atlas] \u2013 Graph words relations in English, French and gives cross representations for translations \u2013 offers 500 searches per user per day.\n\nPlain words synonyms finder:\n* [https://www.synonym-finder.com/ Synonym Finder] \u2013 Synonym finder including hypernyms in search result\n* [http://trovami.altervista.org/sinonimi/en Thesaurus] \u2013 Online synonyms in English, Italian, French and German\n* [http://synonyms.woxikon.com/ Woxikon Synonyms] \u2013 Over 1 million synonyms \u2013 English, German, Spanish, French, Italian, Portuguese, Swedish and Dutch\n* [http://www.findmewords.com/synonyms.html FindMeWords Synonyms] \u2013 Online Synonym Dictionary with definitions\n* [http://www.classicthesaurus.com Classic Thesaurus] \u2013 Crowdsourced synonym dictionary\n* [https://www.powerthesaurus.org/ Power Thesaurus] \u2013 Synonym dictionary with definitions and examples and other references\n* [https://pasttenses.com/ Past Tenses Synonyms] \u2013 Online synonym finding website\n\n{{Lexicology}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Lexical semantics]]\n[[Category:Types of words]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the general meaning of \"synonym\"}}\n{{short description|Words or phrases having the same meaning}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2014}}\n[[File:Library of Ashurbanipal synonym list tablet.jpg|thumb|Synonym list in [[cuneiform]] on a clay tablet, [[Neo-Assyrian]] period<ref>{{British-Museum-db|K.4375|id=308401}}</ref>]]\n\nA '''synonym''' is a word or phrase that means exactly or nearly the same as another word or phrase in the same language. Words that are synonyms are said to be '''synonymous''', and the state of being a synonym is called '''synonymy'''.  For example, the words ''begin'', ''start'', ''commence'', and ''initiate'' are all synonyms of one another. Words are typically synonymous in one particular [[word sense|sense]]: for example, ''long'' and ''extended'' in the [[context (language use)|context]] ''long time'' or ''extended time'' are synonymous, but ''long'' cannot be used in the phrase ''extended family''. Synonyms with exactly the same meaning share a [[seme (semantics)|seme]] or denotational [[sememe]], whereas those with inexactly similar meanings share a broader denotational or [[connotation]]al sememe and thus overlap within a [[semantic field]]. The former are sometimes called [[cognitive synonymy|cognitive synonyms]] and the latter, near-synonyms,<ref name=\"Stanojevi\u0107_2009\">{{Citation |last=Stanojevi\u0107 |first=Maja |year=2009 |title= Cognitive synonymy: a general overview |journal=Facta Universitatis, Linguistics and Literature series |volume=7 |issue=2 |pages=193\u2013200 | url=http://facta.junis.ni.ac.rs/lal/lal200902/lal200902-05.pdf |doi= |postscript=.}}</ref> plesionyms<ref>DiMarco, Chrysanne, and Graeme Hirst. \"Usage notes as the basis for a representation of near-synonymy for lexical choice.\" Proceedings of 9th annual conference of the University of Waterloo Centre for the New Oxford English Dictionary and Text Research. 1993.</ref> or poecilonyms.<ref>Grambs, David. The Endangered English Dictionary: Bodacious Words Your Dictionary Forgot. WW Norton & Company, 1997.</ref>\n\n==Lexicography==\nSome [[lexicographer]]s claim that no synonyms have exactly the same meaning (in all contexts or social levels of language) because [[etymology]], [[orthography]], phonic qualities, [[connotation]]s, ambiguous meanings, [[usage (language)|usage]], and so on make them unique. Different words that are similar in meaning usually differ for a reason: ''feline'' is more formal than ''cat''; ''long'' and ''extended'' are only synonyms in one usage and not in others (for example, a ''long arm'' is not the same as an ''extended arm''). Synonyms are also a source of [[euphemism]]s.\n\n[[M